# Frontend Testing Rules

## 1. Framework Requirements

| Purpose       | Framework                    | Notes                           |
| ------------- | ---------------------------- | ------------------------------- |
| Unit Tests    | Jest + React Testing Library | Default for all component tests |
| E2E Tests     | Playwright                   | Critical user flows only        |
| API Mocking   | MSW (Mock Service Worker)    | For integration tests           |
| Accessibility | jest-axe                     | Automated a11y checks           |

## 2. Query Priority (Accessibility-First)

Use queries in this order - if you can't query accessibly, the UI may not be accessible:

| Priority | Query                  | Use Case                                      |
| -------- | ---------------------- | --------------------------------------------- |
| 1        | `getByRole`            | Interactive elements (buttons, inputs, links) |
| 2        | `getByLabelText`       | Form fields with labels                       |
| 3        | `getByPlaceholderText` | Only if no label exists                       |
| 4        | `getByText`            | Non-interactive text content                  |
| 5        | `getByDisplayValue`    | Current form input values                     |
| 6        | `getByAltText`         | Images                                        |
| 7        | `getByTitle`           | Last resort                                   |
| 8        | `getByTestId`          | **Avoid** - only when nothing else works      |

**NEVER use**: `container.querySelector` or DOM traversal methods.

## 3. Query Variants

| Variant    | Returns           | Use When                              |
| ---------- | ----------------- | ------------------------------------- |
| `getBy*`   | Element or throws | Element SHOULD exist                  |
| `queryBy*` | Element or null   | Asserting element does NOT exist      |
| `findBy*`  | Promise<Element>  | Element appears after async operation |

```typescript
// ✅ Correct usage
screen.getByRole('button') // Element exists
expect(screen.queryByRole('alert')).not.toBeInTheDocument() // Element doesn't exist
await screen.findByRole('button') // Appears after async
```

## 4. Critical Patterns (Not ESLint-Enforced)

### Use `userEvent` over `fireEvent`

```typescript
// ✅ Correct - simulates real user behavior
const user = userEvent.setup()
await user.type(input, 'hello')
await user.click(button)

// ❌ Avoid - low-level, misses events
fireEvent.change(input, { target: { value: 'hello' } })
```

### Single assertion in `waitFor`

```typescript
// ✅ Correct - fast failure
await waitFor(() => expect(element).toBeInTheDocument())
expect(element).toHaveTextContent('success')

// ❌ Avoid - delays failure to timeout
await waitFor(() => {
  expect(element).toBeInTheDocument()
  expect(element).toHaveTextContent('success')
})
```

### No side-effects in `waitFor`

```typescript
// ✅ Correct - side-effects outside
await user.click(button)
await waitFor(() => expect(result).toBeInTheDocument())

// ❌ Avoid - click runs multiple times
await waitFor(() => {
  fireEvent.click(button)
  expect(result).toBeInTheDocument()
})
```

## 5. Project Test Structure

```
__tests__/
├── accessibility/      # jest-axe tests
├── components/         # Unit tests (mirrors components/)
├── hooks/              # Custom hook tests
├── integration/        # Multi-component flows
└── lib/                # Utility function tests
```

**Reference Implementation:**

- Custom render helper: `@__tests__/test-utils.tsx`
- Hook test example: `@__tests__/hooks/use-header-content.test.tsx`
- Component test example: `@__tests__/components/layout/header.test.tsx`

## 6. Test Patterns by Type

### Component Test

```typescript
import { render, screen } from '@testing-library/react'
import userEvent from '@testing-library/user-event'

test('button triggers callback on click', async () => {
  // Arrange
  const handleClick = jest.fn()
  const user = userEvent.setup()
  render(<Button onClick={handleClick}>Submit</Button>)

  // Act
  await user.click(screen.getByRole('button', { name: /submit/i }))

  // Assert
  expect(handleClick).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(1)
})
```

### Hook Test

```typescript
import { renderHook, waitFor } from '@testing-library/react'

test('hook fetches data', async () => {
  const { result } = renderHook(() => useData())

  await waitFor(() => expect(result.current.isSuccess).toBe(true))
  expect(result.current.data).toEqual(expectedData)
})
```

### Async Component Test

```typescript
test('shows loading then data', async () => {
  render(<DataComponent />)

  // Loading state
  expect(screen.getByText(/loading/i)).toBeInTheDocument()

  // Data loaded
  await screen.findByText(/john doe/i)
  expect(screen.queryByText(/loading/i)).not.toBeInTheDocument()
})
```

## 7. What ESLint Enforces

The following are automatically enforced by `eslint-plugin-testing-library` and `eslint-plugin-jest-dom`:

| Rule                         | ESLint Rule                                                      |
| ---------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Use `screen` for queries     | `testing-library/prefer-screen-queries`                          |
| Use `findBy*` for async      | `testing-library/prefer-find-by`                                 |
| No `container.querySelector` | `testing-library/no-container`, `testing-library/no-node-access` |
| No side-effects in `waitFor` | `testing-library/no-wait-for-side-effects`                       |
| No empty `waitFor` callback  | `testing-library/no-wait-for-empty-callback`                     |
| No manual cleanup            | `testing-library/no-manual-cleanup`                              |
| No unnecessary act           | `testing-library/no-unnecessary-act`                             |
| Use jest-dom matchers        | `jest-dom/prefer-*` rules                                        |

See `eslint.config.mjs` for full configuration.

